{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12799"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12799"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.13,0.57,0.07,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77470"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5240"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62982"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2015"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3524"},{"type":"tags","id":"3803"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42811"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77470"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department complaining of fatigue. The patient reports feeling extremely weak over the past few days and almost fainted when she stood up today. She has had a cough, runny nose, and nasal congestion for the past week. Today she began experiencing nausea, vomiting, and severe abdominal pain. She has a history of hypothyroidism, hypertension, and chronic kidney disease. She is currently taking levothyroxine for hypothyroidism and lisinopril for hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her temperature is 38.5 \u00b0C, blood pressure 85/55 mmHg and pulse 126/min. She appears weak and lethargic, and her heart sounds are tachycardic but regular without murmurs. There are occasional rhonchi in her lungs, and her abdomen is diffusely tender, with normal bowel sounds. Laboratory tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esodium 124 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epotassium 5.7 mmol/L (3.5-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecreatinine level of 300 \u00b5mol/L (60-115)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaemoglobin 111 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is diagnosed with influenza and started on intravenous fluids. After receiving 2 L of normal saline, her blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum cortisol","CT abdomen","Intravenous hydrocortisone 100 mg","Cosyntropin stimulation test","Plasma renin concentration"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with symptoms of fatigue, weakness, hypotension, and electrolyte abnormalities (hyponatraemia and hyperkalaemia), which are suggestive of adrenal insufficiency or adrenal crisis. The low sodium with elevated potassium is the typical biochemical pattern of mineralocorticoid deficiency, which occurs with primary but not secondary adrenal insufficiency. Adrenal insufficiency can be life-threatening, and immediate treatment with glucocorticoids is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the patient\u0027s low blood pressure, tachycardia, and laboratory findings indicate the need for prompt glucocorticoid replacement therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice for acute adrenal crisis. It provides immediate glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid activity, stabilising the patient\u0027s condition. Hydrocortisone acts as a replacement for the deficient cortisol, helping to restore blood pressure, normalise electrolyte levels, and improve the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA short synacthen test, also known as the cosyntropin stimulation test,\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold-standard diagnostic test for adrenal insufficiency. However, it is not appropriate to perform this test in an acutely unstable patient who requires immediate treatment. The focus should be on administering hydrocortisone to stabilise the patient, and diagnostic testing can be planned for a later date when the patient\u0027s condition is no longer critical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasuring the serum cortisol level\u003C/strong\u003E can be an initial step in evaluating adrenal insufficiency. A low morning cortisol level, in the context of suggestive clinical presentation and laboratory findings, may be sufficient to confirm the diagnosis. However, a normal cortisol level does not rule out adrenal insufficiency, and further testing like the cosyntropin stimulation test may still be required to definitively establish the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the initial step in the management of adrenal insufficiency or adrenal crisis. While a CT scan may be useful in evaluating the cause of primary adrenal insufficiency, the priority in this acutely ill patient is to start treatment first and then proceed with further investigations to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma renin concentration\u003C/strong\u003E is not the immediate priority in this scenario. While it can be useful in differentiating primary from secondary adrenal insufficiency, the immediate concern is to stabilise the patient with glucocorticoid therapy. Once the patient is stable, further investigations can be conducted to determine the underlying cause of the adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with adrenal insufficiency often present with hypotension, altered mental status, anorexia, vomiting, weight loss, fatigue, and recurrent abdominal pain.","Immediate treatment with glucocorticoids is crucial in suspected adrenal crisis.","Intravenous hydrocortisone provides both glucocorticoid and mineralocorticoid activity."],"references":["Bornstein SR, Allolio B, Arlt W, Barthel A, Don-Wauchope A, Hammer GD, Husebye ES, Merke DP, Murad MH, Stratakis CA, Torpy DJ. Diagnosis and Treatment of Primary Adrenal Insufficiency: An Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2016 Feb;101(2):364-89. doi: 10.1210/jc.2015-1710. Epub 2016 Jan 13. PMID: 26760044; PMCID: PMC4880116. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26760044/","Huecker MR, Bhutta BS, Dominique E. Adrenal Insufficiency. [Updated 2023 Feb 9]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28722862/","Khare S, Anjum F. Adrenocorticotropic Hormone Test. [Updated 2022 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32310400/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62982"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12799"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62982"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T08:46:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T08:46:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5240"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77470"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta